  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>3. Public Access Advocacy & Education</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge high">Essential Skills</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Confidently navigate public access, educate others appropriately, and advocate for your rights</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>Know Your Rights</strong></summary>
        <h4>ADA Quick Reference</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Where Service Dogs Are Allowed:</strong> All public accommodations (restaurants, stores, hotels, medical facilities, etc.)</li>
          <li><strong>Two Legal Questions:</strong> Businesses can only ask:
            <ul>
              <li>"Is that a service dog?"</li>
              <li>"What task does it perform?"</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Cannot Ask:</strong> For documentation, to demonstrate task, about your disability</li>
          <li><strong>Cannot Require:</strong> Vest, ID, certification (though they help)</li>
          <li><strong>Can Remove If:</strong> Dog is out of control and you don't remedy, or dog is not housebroken</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Service Dogs in Training Rights</h4>
        <p><strong>Varies by State:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Some states grant full access to SDiT (service dogs in training)</li>
          <li>Some grant partial access</li>
          <li>Some grant no special access beyond pet-friendly locations</li>
          <li><strong>Look up your state's law:</strong> Search "[your state] service dog in training access laws"</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Response Scripts for Common Situations</strong></summary>
        <h4>Access Challenge: "Is that a real service dog?"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "Yes, she's a service dog." (Smile, stay calm, don't elaborate unless pressed)</p>

        <h4>Breed Discrimination: "We don't allow pitbulls"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "She's a service dog. Under the ADA, breed restrictions don't apply to service animals. Her breed doesn't affect her ability to perform her tasks."</p>
        <p><em>If they persist:</em> "I'd be happy to provide information about ADA service dog regulations. Denying access based on breed is a violation."</p>

        <h4>Documentation Demand: "I need to see her papers"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "The ADA doesn't require documentation for service dogs. You can ask if she's a service dog and what task she performs, which I'm happy to answer."</p>
        <p><em>If you have documentation and want to show it:</em> Fine to offer, but know you're not required to.</p>

        <h4>Invasive Questions: "What's your disability?"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "That's personal medical information I'm not required to share. I'm happy to tell you what task she performs." (Then briefly state task)</p>

        <h4>Task Question: "What does she do?"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "She's trained to assist with my PTSD. She performs tasks like deep pressure therapy during anxiety attacks and guides me to exits when I'm overwhelmed."</p>
        <p><em>Note:</em> Keep it brief, factual, don't over-explain</p>

        <h4>Want to Pet: "Can I pet your dog?"</h4>
        <p><strong>Response:</strong> "She's working right now, so no thank you." (Smile, be polite but firm)</p>
        <p><em>If they're a child:</em> Same answer, maybe add "When dogs are working they need to focus, just like when you're doing homework!"</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>When and How to Escalate</strong></summary>
        <h4>If Access Is Denied Despite Explanation</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Stay Calm:</strong> Getting angry hurts your case</li>
          <li><strong>Ask for Manager:</strong> Speak to highest person available</li>
          <li><strong>Educate:</strong> Provide ADA info (many businesses genuinely don't know)</li>
          <li><strong>Document:</strong> Note date, time, employee names, what was said</li>
          <li><strong>File Complaint:</strong> If unresolved:
            <ul>
              <li>ADA.gov online complaint form</li>
              <li>Department of Justice Civil Rights Division</li>
              <li>State attorney general office</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Decide if Worth Fighting:</strong> Sometimes it's easier to go elsewhere, especially during training</li>
        </ol>

        <h4>When to Walk Away</h4>
        <p>During training phase, sometimes better to:< /p>
        <ul>
          <li>Leave and train elsewhere rather than create confrontation</li>
          <li>File complaint later rather than escalate in moment</li>
          <li>Preserve your energy for training, not fighting</li>
          <li>Return when Gypsy is more advanced and discrimination is clearer violation</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Educating the Public Appropriately</strong></summary>
        <h4>When to Educate</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Genuine, respectful questions from curious people</li>
          <li>Business staff who seem uninformed but well-meaning</li>
          <li>When you have time and energy</li>
          <li>When it might prevent future discrimination</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>When NOT to Educate</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>When you're already stressed/overwhelmed</li>
          <li>When person is hostile or argumentative</li>
          <li>When Gypsy is having a training challenge moment</li>
          <li>When you're in a hurry</li>
          <li>Random strangers approaching in public (unless you choose to)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Educational Resources to Carry</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ADA Service Animal Cards:</strong> Brief summary of rights (print from ADA.gov)</li>
          <li><strong>State SDiT Law:</strong> If your state has one, print or save to phone</li>
          <li><strong>Brief Script:</strong> 2-3 sentences about service dogs and rights</li>
          <li><strong>Business Handout:</strong> One-pager explaining ADA for businesses (if you choose to carry)</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
