  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>4. Building Your Personal Support Network</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge medium">Long-Term Sustainability</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Create a support system for the multi-year journey of service dog training and partnership</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>Types of Support You Need</strong></summary>
        <h4>Training Support</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Fellow Handlers:</strong> People who understand the training journey</li>
          <li><strong>Professional Trainer:</strong> Even 1-2 consult sessions when stuck (see Resources section)</li>
          <li><strong>Training Buddy:</strong> Another handler to practice scenarios with</li>
          <li><strong>Online Communities:</strong> 24/7 access to advice and support</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Emotional Support</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Understanding Friends/Family:</strong> Who get why this matters</li>
          <li><strong>Therapist/Counselor:</strong> For PTSD management alongside service dog work</li>
          <li><strong>Veteran Community:</strong> Who understand military trauma</li>
          <li><strong>Service Dog Community:</strong> Who understand training challenges</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Practical Support</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Emergency Contact:</strong> Can care for Gypsy if you're hospitalized (see Emergency section)</li>
          <li><strong>Training Helper:</strong> Can play "distraction person" or help practice tasks</li>
          <li><strong>Transportation:</strong> If you don't drive, someone who can help get to training locations</li>
          <li><strong>Financial:</strong> Info on grants, fundraising if needed (see Resources section)</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Finding Your Training Buddy</strong></summary>
        <h4>Why a Training Buddy Helps</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Practice public access together (safety in numbers)</li>
          <li>Dogs can help desensitize each other (controlled dog exposure)</li>
          <li>Accountability and motivation</li>
          <li>Share resources and problem-solving</li>
          <li>Emotional support from someone in same boat</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Where to Find One</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Online service dog groups - post "looking for training buddy in [city]"</li>
          <li>Local dog training classes (not all service dog specific)</li>
          <li>VA service dog programs or support groups</li>
          <li>Service dog friendly locations - chat with other handlers you see</li>
          <li>Local veteran organizations</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>What to Look For</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Similar training timeline (both in early/middle/late training)</li>
          <li>Compatible training philosophies (both positive reinforcement)</li>
          <li>Similar location/schedule for meeting up</li>
          <li>Good communication and reliability</li>
          <li>Respectful of each other's disabilities and boundaries</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Dealing with Isolation</strong></summary>
        <h4>Why Service Dog Training Can Be Isolating</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Can't always go places due to training challenges</li>
          <li>Friends/family may not understand the commitment</li>
          <li>PTSD itself often causes social withdrawal</li>
          <li>Public interactions can be draining (questions, discrimination)</li>
          <li>Training takes time that used to go to social activities</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Strategies to Combat Isolation</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Online Community:</strong> Engage daily in Facebook groups, even just reading posts</li>
          <li><strong>Virtual Meetups:</strong> Some communities have Zoom check-ins or training discussions</li>
          <li><strong>Include Friends in Training:</strong> Invite supportive friends to be "distractions" or come on training outings</li>
          <li><strong>Celebrate Milestones:</strong> Share progress with your community (post photos, updates)</li>
          <li><strong>Remember the Goal:</strong> This isolation is temporary; service dog enables MORE social participation long-term</li>
          <li><strong>Balance:</strong> Still make time for non-dog activities and relationships</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
  </article>

  <div class="alert alert-success">
